video_title: 3. Multiplication and Inverse Matrices
Comment: In 25:50 , An alternative way to understand that matrix A does not have an Inverse is to visualize the matrix in a cartesian plane. The matrix is composed of two vectors: (1,2) & (3,6). Plotting these two vectors you will realize that they are parallel. Thus, they do not create a D2 area. They are a D1 line, one on top of the other. Reversing such vectors applying( the inverse matrix) would result in a zero D point, specifically (0,0). Thus, there is no inverse matrix for matrix A. Note: Finding that the determinant of the matrix A is equal to 0 would quickly depict this same process.
